puts forward a new theory that highlights the crucial differences between local, state, and national democracies. Being small in size, limited in power, and largely unbiased in distributing their resources, local governments are "managerial democracies" with a distinct style of electoral politics. Instead of hinging on the partisanship, ideology, and group appeals that define national and state elections, local elections are based on the custodial performance of civic-oriented leaders and on their personal connections to voters with similarly deep community ties. Explaining not only the dynamics of local elections, Oliver's findings also upend many long-held assumptions about community power and local governance, including the importance of voter turnout and the possibilities for grassroots political change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aLocal electionsxUnited States. 0aLocal electionszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Local.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAmerican government.  aAmerican municipalities.  aAmerican politics.  abias.  acity council members.  aclassical democratic theory.  aconstitutive power.  acustodial performance.  aelection results.  aelectoral politics.  agrassroots politics.  ahomevoters.  aincumbent.  aintermunicipal political exclusion.  alocal community.  alocal democracy.  alocal elections.  alocal governance.  alocal government.  alocal politicians.  alocal politics.  amanagerial democracy.  amunicipal government.  amunicipal governments.  amunicipalities.  anational elections.  anational politics.  apolitical candidates.  apolitical dynamics.  apolitical engagement.  apolitical participation.  apopulation size.  aresource distrib